[2026-03-13T17:54:42Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WfRSSLEYordsLkAqLcb4bM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to update the web handler test. The existing tests need to be updated because the behavior has changed:\n\n1. \"one failed\" test: `[succeeded, running, failed]` - with old logic this returns \"failed\" (highest priority), but with new logic, running outweighs terminal, so it should be \"running\".\n\n2. \"failed beats running\" test: `[running, failed]` - with old logic \"failed\" wins, but with new logic, running (active) outweighs failed (terminal), so \"running\" wins.\n\n3. \"cancelled beats succeeded\" test: `[succeeded, cancelled]` - both are terminal now. With no StartedAt set, both have zero time. \n\nWhen StartedAt is zero across all runs, the \"most recent\" logic will just pick the first one in iteration order since none of the time comparisons will trigger. This means the test behavior depends on which run comes first, which isn't ideal but is how it works when `NewRun` doesn't set StartedAt.\n\nLooking at the test expectations, the \"cancelled beats succeeded\" case expects \"cancelled\" but would actually return \"succeeded\" since it comes first in the slice. I need to redesign these test cases to align with the actual behavior: runs with active states take priority, and when all are terminal with the same timestamp, the first one wins. I see the issue now—when all runs have zero StartedAt, the logic just picks the first one, so \"cancelled beats succeeded\" actually returns \"succeeded\" since that's first in the list. The test name doesn't match the behavior anymore since recency determines the winner among terminal states, not a fixed priority. I need to restructure this test with actual StartedAt values to properly validate the recency logic, and I should also verify the integration test still works correctly with the updated status resolution. I need to handle the zero-time case in tests where StartedAt isn't set—either by updating tests to include proper StartedAt values for recency-dependent cases, or by implementing a graceful fallback. Since the zero-time approach works fine when all runs share the same state, I'll restructure the web handler unit tests to set StartedAt values where the active-vs-terminal logic matters, then update the test expectations accordingly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":838,"cache_read_input_tokens":81656,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":838},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"672a244f-d306-4bfb-8514-5ea42ce22c11","uuid":"ebd402e1-db62-48f3-9259-e863cc35ee32"}
